        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>balloons (aircraft) [300222189], lighter than air aircraft [300216066], aircraft by form [300220406], aircraft [300212527], air and space transportation vehicles [300222210], vehicles (transportation) [300219258], Transportation Vehicles (hierarchy name) [300042929], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Balloons of nonextensible material, usually spherical or pear-shaped, open on the bottom and held aloft by the introduction of heated air; they are designed to rise and travel into the atmosphere. Hot-air balloons typically have a container, usually a basket large enough to carry people, suspended below.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000027841/McGraw-Hill Encyclopedia of Science and Technology (1992)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Úsese para designar un globo de material no extensible, por lo general esférico, que se mantiene elevado por medio de aire caliente generado sobre un contenedor, normalmente una cesta, lo suficientemente grande como para transportar personas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Te gebruiken voor meestal ronde ballonnen van een niet-rekbaar materiaal, die in de lucht worden gehouden door hete lucht die wordt geproduceerd boven een bak, vaak een mand, en groot genoeg zijn om mensen de atmosfeer in te dragen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Ballon aus einem nicht dehnbaren Material, gewöhnlich kugelförmig oder birnenförmig, am Boden offen und in der Höhe gehalten durch das Einleiten von heißer Luft; entworfen, um aufzusteigen und in der Atmosphäre zu fahren. Der Heißluftballon hat typischerweise einen unterhalb hängenden Behälter, gewöhnlich einen Korb, der groß genug ist, um Personen zu befördern.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
